I speak on behalf of every law-abiding, tax-paying hard working ethnic minority in the UK when I say we do not want such illegal migrants here, especially those who put our daughters in danger. I speak as the son of two LEGAL immigrants from India to the UK. I am the exact demographic of the very person these lefties say wants more immigration. I am the grandson of a very prominent Indian socialist. I come from a family of champagne socialists. I know the immigrant lifestyle and the challenges that come along with it. Please read to the end and write your comments below.



I have relatives in the USA and India. None of whom will speak to me because of one reason- I support Donald Trump. However, what I write here is not for political gain. 

In a limited capacity, I have served in Her Majesty‚Äôs Armed Forces. I have friends who served in Northern Ireland, Syria, and Afghanistan who never came home. I have also done fitness training for several HM Armed Forces members.



A hugely disproportionate number of crimes are committed by illegal immigrants. On behalf of every law-abiding tax paying, hard-working 2nd generation ethnic minority who lives in the UK I openly say we do not want such people here, What amazes me is that PM Rishi Sunak is also the son of two legal immigrants but he is letting them in! I am amazed he does not have the same views as me when it comes to immigration! 



Here is my stance on immigration.



Genuine political prisoner. No problem.

A genuine asylum seeker. No problem.



On that note, I find it reprehensible that we did not offer asylum to Asia Bibby or Rahaf Mohammed.



Asia Bibby was a Pakistani Christian who spent 10 years in prison and was freed on appeal against her conviction on blasphemy charges. Rahaf Mohammed was the Saudi Arabian woman who left her religion and fled a forced arranged marriage. She ended up being rescued by the Canadians who gave her asylum.



Such people will move heaven and earth to give back to the country that gave them refuge. In Asia Bibby‚Äôs case I believe she should have been given a police escort to the nearest British Embassy and their airlifted out by helicopter. She should have been flown to India and then onto the UK. She should have been received by a representative of Her Majesty‚Äôs government and told ‚Äúyou are safe now; this is you now your home.‚Äù 



I promise you she would have moved heaven an earth to contribute to our society.



I give credit to the Danish government who gave refuge to Nadia Nadim. At the age of 12 she saw the Taliban murder her father. She escaped to Denmark with her mother. She now speaks 12 languages. She was a professional footballer who once played for Manchester City. She has scored 200 club goals and 2 for Denmark.  Now her playing days are over she is studying medicine at the University of Copenhagen and aims to become a surgeon.



I welcome such refugees all day long because they contribute.



Non-asylum seekers must fulfil certain criteria



They must come legally.



They must have a reasonable command of English.



They must respect UK law.



They must respect UK culture.



They must Non Hatefully contribute to our society.



I am wholly opposed to mass immigration. I advocate controlled quality immigration.



Let‚Äôs take my dad.



He is an immigrant from India in 1969. The world‚Äôs most devout Hindu. He never claimed a penny in benefit. He arrived in the UK with ¬£5. The following day he was at work in a hospital in a pre-arranged job. He was fluent in the English language. He was a family doctor for over 30 years. He employed 10‚Äì15 people and paid at least ¬£30,000 a year in taxes. His only criminal offence was to get a parking ticket which was quashed on appeal when he proved he was seeing a patient with a heart attack and had to park in an emergency. If any family member ever went on welfare, he would insist that whilst on welfare you worked voluntarily at a charity shop to give back. He gave a lot of money to charity.



At first, some hospital consultants refused to take his referrals. Some local GPs refused to do out-of-hours cover with him. They tried to get him struck off because he started a scheme with a local pharmacy. Under that scheme you would put in your request for a repeat prescription, the local pharmacy would pick it up, and then two days later it would be dispensed and ready at that pharmacy. They had to throw out the complaint because his patients loved it. It saved them time.



All patients with a long-term illness were seen every 3 months to keep their symptoms under control. Hence, they rarely needed hospital referrals. It also kept his waiting list down. He hired loads of nurses to do specialist clinics e.g., high blood pressure clinics. At one stage he was doing so many the health authority made a complaint to the minister of health because he was claiming so much money from them. The minister wrote back and told them to leave him alone and tell other doctors to do the same.



During the latter stages of his career government targets stated that emergency patients were seen within 3 days. He saw them on the SAME day.



As time went on the tables turned. Patients from other practices came to him. He exceeded all government targets and the other doctors were humiliated when the health authority had no choice but to ask him to design protocols to have such an efficient practice.



For the reasons above his patients loved him.



That is how you win people over-you gain their respect.

I defy you to find ONE patriot who opposes such immigrants.

Comment Text:
Immigration and racism have long been issues that Dublin, like many other cities around the world, has struggled with. In recent years, the city has seen an influx of immigrants from different countries, which has brought about a number of challenges. The issue of immigration racism has become particularly prominent in Dublin in 2023.

Immigrants have faced significant difficulties in integrating into Irish society. Many have been met with hostility and discrimination from native Dubliners who view them as a threat to their way of life. This has resulted in widespread racism and prejudice against immigrants, which has manifested in a variety of forms. Some immigrants have been subject to verbal abuse, while others have faced physical violence. This type of treatment is unacceptable and runs counter to the principles of equality and diversity that Ireland prides itself on.

The root cause of immigration racism in Dublin can be traced back to a number of factors, including a lack of understanding and education about different cultures, fear of the unknown, and misinformation. This is further exacerbated by the rise of far-right political groups that spread hateful messages and incite violence against immigrants.

To tackle the issue of immigration racism in Dublin, it is important to address the underlying causes and work to break down the barriers that separate different groups of people. This requires a concerted effort from the government, community leaders, and individual citizens.

The government must take a proactive approach in addressing immigration racism by introducing and enforcing laws that protect the rights of immigrants and promote equality and diversity. This includes providing education and awareness programs to educate the public about different cultures and encouraging dialogue between different communities.

Community leaders play a crucial role in promoting understanding and tolerance between different groups of people. They can work to bring people together and promote Non Hateful relationships between different communities. They can also challenge harmful attitudes and beliefs and provide support to those who have been the victim of immigration racism.

Individual citizens also have a responsibility to challenge immigration racism in their own communities. This includes speaking out against hate speech and promoting understanding and respect for different cultures. By doing so, individuals can play a significant role in creating a more inclusive and accepting society for all.

In conclusion, immigration racism is a major issue in Dublin 2023, and it is important to address it head-on. By working together, the government, community leaders, and individual citizens can create a society that is welcoming and inclusive to all. Only by doing so can Dublin fulfill its potential as a truly diverse and multicultural city.

Comment Text:
I'm going to put in my two cents, and I know this is youtube comments where no one will listen, but I'll do it anyway. 

While I'm all for stopping illegal immigration (as everyone rightfully should be, there's a reason we have protocols and rules for immigrants to enter the country), too many people lean into the more overarching message of "no immigrants or refugees at all", which is a problem. 

Ireland has historically been very reliant on other countries for our people to emigrate to, and our ancestors themselves have faced fierce persecution when emigrating to other countries. To participate in the same persecution as we faced with people who wish to come to our fair Isle for a new life is nothing short of hypocritical and wrong. Illegal immigration is not a big problem in Ireland, thats the truth. We have only 1 land border, and that's with another nation on the island and thus its very hard for any immigrants to get here illegally. Airport travel and boat travel are heavily monitored to the point where it is near impossible to get to Ireland illegally. We're also not exactly the prime candidate for illegal immigration when countries like Germany and France offer far better opportunities and are much easier to reach. You got to remember, non-EU immigrants have to illegaly go through multiple countries before even getting close to Ireland (Which is not as easy as onw would think). Other EU countries are also more prosperous than Ireland and are more well known to uneducated immigrants and thus are more attractive. 

The fact of the matter is people are misinformed on the subject, and while they might not like to admit it, it's true. We must face the truth we are all ignoring and realise the "fight against immigration" is merely only a tool used by elite beaurocrats to get themselves elected into government. If we accept this madeup "fight" the elite have invented, we will only be fighting amongst ourselves.  We cannot be their pawns. We must see past the lies and mistruths they tell us and realise we should not be striving to hurt others in our economic class, but to demand change from rhe very top of the national government. 

We have plenty of legal immigration in ireland, and while people may complain about it, it is a natural state of any wealthy modern nation. We need immigrants for trade jobs, lower paid jobs and skilled immigrants for our healthcare system and government services. We are already suffering shortages in trades workers and skilled medical practitioners. By protesting immigration we are further hurting these sectors and it will cause even more problems for our nation. I think that while these protests are from a good place, they lead to the wrong results. 

And as for refugees, while yes it is a strain on our government and this Isle, it is our responsibility as a modern and prosperous nation to help our European brothers. For too long Ireland has been isolated through British rule, only in the last century have we branched out and been part of a regional community. And it is to our benefit to help those in that community, so that in the future they may help us. Only together is Europe strong. If we all fell back to individual nations once more, we would simply become easy pickings for economic super powers like America and China. Thus it is essential for us to be a unified front. It is why Brexit was so idiotic for Britain. They have given up the strength of the many for the pride of the few. We will not make the same mistake.

I hope other Irish people realise this in time. We cannot deny others the rights of immigration and safety when we ourselves have taken use of those concepts in the past from others. I pray that we see last the fog clouding our eyes and instead fight for meaningful changes that will change Ireland as a whole for the better.

Actually there were a lot of supports available in many countries Irish people travelled to on coffin ships.

Australia had lodgings and offered work if plans fell through. In Canada, money was paid to get people to where their point of contact would be, sometimes paying their way from quebec to Toronto or further, and similarly in New York and American ports.

Racism wasn't quite as big of an issue at that specific time, but there definitely was tensions and discrimination against catholics for decades, and if there was somehow a civil rights movement earlier in the history of the US, that would also have been brought up.
